This is the only real French bakery I’ve ever found stateside. People are raving about the croissants and pastries, and those are indeed excellent, but it’s the baguettes I come for. Crusty, golden, big-bubbled airy bake, these are serious - none of that sad namby-pamby supermarket stuff that folds over on itself when you try to spread butter on it. When La Boulangerie goes to the Logan farmer’s market with their bread, they always have the longest line around. Everyone knows how good it is.

The review is strictly about the baguette quality which I feel has diminished over time. I hesitate to leave this review on La Boulangerie baguettes especially because everything else I've tried has been great (excellent quiche and pain au chocolat) and pastries beautifully crafted.  The baguettes I've purchased though (at their Logan Square Farmers Market stall) are not the crusty on the outside traditional French style they made in the past and common in the few bakeries that exist in the city baking traditional artisan French baguettes, but it appears they may have modified the baguette ingredients, possibly to prolong its shelf life and/or to appeal to customers' palettes. The crust is somewhat softer (see picture I posted pressing down on a second day old baguette) and appears to be somewhat spongy, and prettier but quality is a bit like grocery store baguettes that have industrial additives like dough conditioners to keep them from getting hard, and the taste difference is subtly noticeable. I understand the need to make modifications to be able to mass produce, adapt to the palettes and stay profitable if the case but unfortunate when quality is affected.   I was happy when I learned La Boulangerie was making its return to the Logan Square area (bakeries like Floriole, Hewn or La Fournette are farther away) but I'm now willing to trek out of the neighborhood for a simple traditional baguette. I may be unaware but possibly the traditional ones are sold at their brick and mortar location(s) and not at the farmers market? But if not the case, and what I purchased is considered their basic baguette, it's disappointing. The reviews on here overall are favorable regarding La Boulangerie and much of it deserved, and I may be the odd person out regarding their baguettes and may be a little spoiled after living abroad, but felt it's important to leave a fair review. La Boulangerie, if you're reading, hopefully you'll consider returning to selling simple traditional baguette even once in a while at the farmers market. Thanks

This review comes after a few mixed experiences. First, when I discovered they use cheap deli ham on the Parisian, I asked for the Bayonne Ham substitution, as that is how I've always had it in France. However, after purchasing it this way a few times over the course of weeks, they suddenly told me that it was a "dollar upcharge". When I asked if this was a new policy, the counter girl just stared at me, said "let me check" and then made me wait over five minutes while she whispered about me to another counter girl while waiting on her manager.  Another time I ordered a different sandwich, and it was suppose to have "mixed greens" but came with spinach. It was horrible. They told me they ran out of mixed greens afterward when I complained that I was basically eating a pile of raw spinach that overshadowed the rest of the sandwich.  Lastly, the one time I ordered a croissant, it was hard and stale.  Each thing can be dismissed on it's own, but after piling up, I was compelled to write this. Every other review gushes about how this is the best in the city, which isn't true. It's just the only thing Logan Square has to offer and is hit or miss. It also seems like they may have raised the prices on their macarons.
